2026-04-05 | Decode Slanted Transposition Cipher

	Question
Return the original string before encoding.

	Approach
1.	Compute number of columns:
		cols = encodedText.length() / rows  

2.	Reconstruct matrix row-wise:
		fill matrix using encodedText  

3.	Read diagonally:
		for each starting column:
			move (i++, j++)  

4.	Build original string  

5.	Remove trailing spaces  

	Time Complexity
	O(n)

	Space Complexity
	O(n)

	Solution

class Solution {
public:
    string decodeCiphertext(string encodedText, int rows) {

        if(rows == 0) return "";

        int n = encodedText.size();
        int cols = n / rows;

        vector<vector<char>> mat(rows, vector<char>(cols));

        int idx = 0;

        // fill row-wise
        for(int i = 0; i < rows; i++){
            for(int j = 0; j < cols; j++){
                mat[i][j] = encodedText[idx++];
            }
        }

        string result = "";

        // read diagonally
        for(int start = 0; start < cols; start++){
            int i = 0, j = start;

            while(i < rows && j < cols){
                result += mat[i][j];
                i++;
                j++;
            }
        }

        // remove trailing spaces
        while(!result.empty() && result.back() == ' ')
            result.pop_back();

        return result;
    }
};

	Key Insight
Encoding was:
		diagonal fill → row read  

So decoding is:
		row fill → diagonal read  

This reverse simulation reconstructs the original string efficiently.
